Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 450 degrees. Bring a large #pot{} of @salt{} water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Halve @zucchini{1} lengthwise; slice into ½-inch-thick half-moons. Dice @tomato{1} into ½-inch pieces. Peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}.

Pat @pork tenderloin{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; season all over with half the @Tuscan Heat Spice{1%tablespoon}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tablespoon} in a large pan over medium heat. Add pork and cook, turning occasionally, until browned all over, ~{4-8%minutes}. Turn off heat; transfer pork to one side of a #baking sheet{}. Wipe out pan.

Toss zucchini with a drizzle of oil, salt, and pepper on opposite side of baking sheet with pork.

Roast on top rack until pork is cooked through and zucchini is lightly browned and tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Once water is boiling, add @spaghetti{6%ounce} to pot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}. Reserve 1 cup pasta cooking water, then drain.

When pasta has 5 minutes left, heat a drizzle of oil in pan used for pork over medium heat. Add tomato and garlic; cook, stirring, until softened and fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Whisk in ¼ cup reserved pasta cooking water, @cream cheese{2%tablespoon}, and @chicken stock concentrate{1}. Cook, stirring, until thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper. Remove from heat.

Add drained spaghetti, zucchini, half the @parmesan cheese{3%tablespoon}, a splash of reserved pasta cooking water, and a drizzle of @olive oil{1%teaspoon} to pan with sauce; toss to combine.

> TIP: If needed, stir in more pasta cooking water a splash at a time until pasta is thoroughly coated in sauce.

Slice pork crosswise.

Divide spaghetti between plates; top with pork and sprinkle with remaining Parmesan. Serve.

> Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.